    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the RV Loan Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our free RV loan calculator helps you estimate the cost of financing a recreational vehicle before you buy. Enter the RV price or the amount you plan to finance after your down payment, the annual interest rate from your lender, and the loan term in years. The calculator instantly shows your monthly payment, total amount paid, and total interest. RV loans can span much longer terms than car loans, so understanding the true cost of financing is essential before committing.
      </p>
      <p>
        Recreational vehicle financing is unique because the wide range of RV types, from small travel trailers to luxury Class A motorhomes, means loan amounts, terms, and rates vary dramatically. A $15,000 pop-up camper loan looks very different from a $200,000 diesel pusher loan. Use this calculator to compare scenarios and find the financing structure that matches your budget and travel goals.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>RV Financing Options and Rates</h2>
      <p>
        RV loan rates typically range from 5% to 10% for secured loans, with the best rates reserved for borrowers with excellent credit financing newer motorhomes. Credit unions, banks, and specialized RV lenders all offer recreational vehicle financing. Credit unions frequently offer the most competitive rates, often 1% to 2% below bank rates. Dealer financing is convenient but may include rate markups. Always compare at least three lending sources before finalizing your RV purchase.
      </p>

      <h3>Extended Loan Terms for RVs</h3>
      <p>
        One unique aspect of RV financing is the availability of extended loan terms. While car loans typically max out at 72 to 84 months, RV loans can stretch to 15 or even 20 years for high-value units. This dramatically reduces monthly payments but also increases total interest. For example, a $45,000 RV loan at 6.5% costs about $19,742 in total interest over 10 years, but that jumps to $31,893 over 15 years and $44,811 over 20 years. Choose the shortest term you can afford to minimize total cost.
      </p>

      <h3>New vs. Used RV Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        New RVs depreciate rapidly, often losing 20% to 30% of their value in the first year alone. A 2 to 3 year old used RV can offer substantial savings while still being in excellent condition. However, new RVs come with full manufacturer warranties and may qualify for lower interest rates and longer loan terms. Used RV loans often have shorter maximum terms and slightly higher rates. Consider the total cost of ownership, including the purchase price, financing costs, insurance, storage, and maintenance, when deciding between new and used.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is a good interest rate for an RV loan?</h3>
      <p>
        RV loan interest rates typically range from 5% to 10% for secured loans, depending on your credit score, loan amount, and term. Borrowers with excellent credit financing new Class A motorhomes can secure rates as low as 4.5%. Used RV loans and smaller units like travel trailers may carry rates 1-2% higher.
      </p>

      <h3>How long can you finance an RV?</h3>
      <p>
        RV loan terms can range from 5 to 20 years, with some lenders offering up to 20-year terms for high-value motorhomes priced over $50,000. Travel trailers and smaller units typically qualify for terms of 5 to 12 years. Longer terms reduce monthly payments but significantly increase total interest paid over the life of the loan.
      </p>

      <h3>How much should I put down on an RV?</h3>
      <p>
        Most lenders require a 10% to 20% down payment on an RV loan. Putting 20% or more down helps you qualify for better rates and avoids being upside-down on the loan, since RVs can depreciate 20% or more in the first year. Some lenders offer lower down payment options for borrowers with excellent credit.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I deduct RV loan interest on my taxes?</h3>
      <p>
        If your RV has sleeping, cooking, and bathroom facilities, it may qualify as a second home under IRS rules, making the loan interest potentially tax deductible under the mortgage interest deduction. The total qualifying mortgage debt (primary home plus RV) is capped at $750,000. Consult a tax professional to confirm eligibility.
      </p>

      <h3>Is it better to buy a new or used RV?</h3>
      <p>
        Used RVs can save you 30% to 50% compared to new, since depreciation is steepest in the first 3 to 5 years. However, new RVs come with manufacturer warranties and may qualify for lower interest rates. A 2-3 year old used RV often offers the best balance of value and reliability, with significant depreciation already absorbed by the first owner.
      </p>

